questiontext.text:
Properties of exponential functions

Whenever we plot exponential functions there are certain properties that we need to be aware of. Consider the function \(y = e^x\). Some important properties are listed below

  1. The domain of \(y= e^x\) is \(-\infty < x < \infty\), and the range is \(0 < y < \infty\) (in particular \(e^x >0\) for all \(x\));
  2. \(e^{x_1+ x_2} = e^{x_1} e^{x_2}\);
  3. \(e^{x_1x_2} = \left(e^{x_1}\right)^{x_2}\);
  4. \(e^{-x} = \frac{1}{e^x}\); and
  5. \(e^{x_1} < e^{x_2}\) if \(x_1 < x_2\) (this says that \(y=e^x\) is an increasing function).

We shall also consider the behaviour of the function for very large positive or negative values of \(x\).  We will not define these ideas rigorously, but the meaning is intuitively clear.  For very large positive values of \(x\), the value of \(y = e^x\) gets arbitrarily large, and we say that \(y=e^x\) tends to \(+\infty\) as \(x\) tends to \(+\infty\).  Similarly, for very large negative values of \(x\), the value of \(y=e^x\) gets arbitrarily close to \(0\), and we say that \(y=e^x\) tends to \(0\) as \(x\) tends to \(-\infty\).
